Reasoning: The claim that higher initial mortality is associated with antidepressant use is strongly supported by evidence from a population-based cohort study (Paper ID: 5691302). This study, focusing on older people, found that antidepressant use was associated with increased all-cause mortality. Specifically, the absolute risk over 1 year for all-cause mortality was 7.04% for patients not taking antidepressants, compared to 8.12% for those taking tricyclic antidepressants, 10.61% for selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors, and 11.43% for other antidepressants (prop_1606, prop_1607, prop_1608, prop_1609). The study also reported a hazard ratio of 1.66 (95% confidence interval 1.56 to 1.77) for all-cause mortality associated with the group of other antidepressants (prop_1599), and a general hazard ratio for all-cause mortality of 1.46 to 1.84 for people taking antidepressants (prop_1604). While the study acknowledges limitations as an observational study (susceptible to confounding by indication, channelling bias, and residual confounding), the consistent findings across different antidepressant classes provide strong evidence for the association.
